In order to improve the sensitivity of the search, several kinematic variables are identified to distinguish between signal and background, and are combined into a boosted decision tree (BDT) multivariate discriminant [91] that uses the AdaBoost algorithm [92]. The BDT is trained to discriminate between signal events with an a-boson mass of 60 GeV and tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t} $$\end{document} events. As described below, the variables chosen as input for the BDT do not depend strongly on the value of ma\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_a$$\end{document} and provide excellent separation between signal and background, so training each mass hypothesis separately with these variables would only slightly improve the sensitivity of the search. The training is performed separately for each of the channels (3j, 3b), (4j, 3b) and (4j, 4b) since the signal and background kinematics differ between them.

