The distributions of the final discriminants in the eight analysis channels considered are combined to test the presence of a signal. The BDT discriminant, described in Sect. 5.1, is used for the channels enriched with signal, (3j, 3b), (4j, 3b) and (4j, 4b), while the HT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$H_{\text {T}} $$\end{document} distribution is used in the five control channels. The statistical analysis is based on a binned likelihood function constructed as a product of Poisson probability terms over all bins considered in the search.

